Introduction¶

This dataset contains more than 10,000 records of movies including their budget, revenue, cast, directors, genres, release year etc. Even though many different analysis can be made with this data, I personally chose to go into detail regarding the different genres and their popularity through the years and the 1 or 2 factors that affect the popularity of the movie.

Import the required packages for your analysis.

Data Cleaning¶

From the above detailed description of columns and data of the TMDB dataset we can see that there are a lot of unwanted columns with respect to our analysis, difference in the data count in different columns and we also have to check whether the correct data type has been given to the columns we are considering for our analysis.

This can be done by data cleaning.

  1. First we have to drop out the uneccessary columns for our analysis.
  2. Secondly we have to check for NULL values or missing values and either update them with the mean value of the columns or else remove these data.
  3. Thirdly we have to ensure that there no duplicates in the dataset.
  4. Fourthly check whether the proper data types are assigned to the columns required for our analysis.
  5. Lastly we have to create another data frame to get only the required columns for our analysis.(This depends on our analysis).
In [15]:
#to drop out uneccessary columns
df_movies.drop(['imdb_id', 'homepage', 'tagline', 'keywords', 'overview', 'production_companies', 
                'release_date','vote_count', 'budget_adj','revenue_adj'], axis=1, inplace=True)

Looking through the data we can see that there are outliers present in the popularity data. So inorder to get rid of that or limit the effect of the outliers we define a function "standardize" which standardizes the values.

In [8]:
# function to standardize the values in dataframe so that it limits the effect of the outliers
def standardize(p):
    p_std = (p - p.mean()) / p.std(ddof = 0)
    return p_std

After defining the "standardize" function, next we standardize the different numerical values which we use for our analysis so that the effect of the outliers would be reduced in our analysis.

In [9]:

Now we can calculate the co-relation co-efficient value to know how the budget and popularity values are related.

In [11]:
# co relation coefficient(Pearson's value)
(popularity_std * budget_std).mean()
Out[11]:
0.47925181029936187

The Pearson's coefficient value is a positive value which denotes that there is a strong relationship between the popularity of a movie and its budget, proportionally. Therefore budget is one of the factors deciding the popularity of the movie.

Now we can represent this distribution using a scatter plot.

In [17]:
plt.figure(figsize=(8, 8))
plt.ylabel('Standardized Popularity')
plt.xlabel('Standardized Budget')
plt.title('Effect of Budget on Popularity of movies')
plt.scatter(x=budget_std, y=popularity_std);

Research Question 2 - Which genre is the most popular and it's transition through the years.¶

Here we explore the genres of the films. We analyse the data and come to a conclusion regarding which genre is the most popular through the years. We get the relationship between the number of films under each genre and then get the one with the most number of films released under it. For that we fist read the edited csv file.

In [32]:

In the given data the multiple genres are given in a single row seperated by a '|' de limiter. So first we have to change that normal single values for each film i.e a film "A" having genres "action|adventure|mystery" should be changed to "A" - action(col1) "A" - adventure(col2) and "A" - mystery(col3). The below codes does that.

In [33]:
#to split the genres into different columns
a = lambda x: pd.Series([i for i in (x.split('|'))])
df_genre = df['genres'].apply(a)
df_genre.head()
Out[33]:
0 1 2 3 4
0 Action Adventure Science Fiction Thriller NaN
1 Action Adventure Science Fiction Thriller NaN

Conclusions¶

Thus the most popular genre in most of the years is Drama. The table gives a list of the most popular genres from 1960 to 2015. The plots shows the distribution of the different genres over the years in the given dataset.

The movie's budget plays a crucial role in the popularity of the film which is proved from the Pearson's coefficient which is calculated form the cleaned budget and popularity dataset. But since there was lack of data regarding budget we cannot entirely rely on the data remaining after cleaning to determine whether the above stated relationship is true. From the cleaned dataset we have arrived at the relationship. Almost half the dataset was removed cause of unavailability of budget details. Therefore the above stated relationship is paritally true. The same goes for the observations regarding the runtime of a movie as well as the revenue collected and its effect on popularity. The runtime also plays a crucial role in the popularity of a movie as observed above. The popularity of the film gets reflected on the revenue as well. More popular the film more revenue it gives.

Since there were less data regarding the budget and revenue the conclusions made could not be definite. With limited values the analysis will also be difficult. The point I would like to explore in future will be thr effect of the cast in the popularity of a movie. How effective is the cast in a movies' success is the point I wish to explore in future. Also I would like to observe the same for the directors as well.

Will the popularity of actors and directors alone create a positive voting for the film? Will it be enough to make a movie a success? Or are there other factors responsible for the same? These are the future observations whihc I would like to look into.

Apart from this a detailed description of the columns in the data set should also have been included. Since it was a very common dataset the data was easy enough to understand but a brief explanation on the purposes of the various columns could have been an added advantage.
